message.content:
=You are conducting research to create a hyper-personalized cold email for a sales lead to promote DropStop.

Rules:
- Use only factual, verifiable, recent info (last 12 months)
- If no data exists for a field, write exactly: "No relevant data found"
- Return ONLY valid JSON — no Markdown, no code fences, no commentary
- Do not wrap the JSON in a string. The value of `message.content` must be an actual JSON object, not a quoted string.
- Double quotes required around all keys and string values
- Arrays preferred for lists (e.g., news items, challenges, product-fit angles)

Lead Information:
Name: {{ $json.name }}
Email: {{ $json.email }}
LinkedIn: {{ $json.linkedin_url }}
Job Title: {{ $json.title }}
Headline: {{ $json.headline }}
Industry: {{ $json.industry }}
Seniority Level: {{ $json.seniority }}

Company Information:
Company Name: {{ $json.organization_name }}
Website: {{ $json.organization_website_url }}
Short Description: {{ $json.organization_short_description }}
Location: {{ $json.city }}, {{ $json.state }}, {{ $json.country }}

Output schema (must match exactly):

{
  "recent_news_and_context": ["string", "..."] | "No relevant data found",
  "role_and_background": "string" | "No relevant data found",
  "pain_points_and_challenges": ["string", "..."] | "No relevant data found",
  "potential_product_market_fit_angles": ["string", "string", "string"]
}

Validate your JSON before returning it. Return ONLY this JSON object.

parameters.jsonSchemaExample:
{
  "selected_employee": {
    "colleague_name": "Jane Doe",
    "title": "Vice President of Business Development",
    "reason": "Jane is a VP overseeing revenue growth and sales strategy—clearly a decision maker"
  }
}
